Introduction to Julia

Julia is a young, free, open-source and promising general-purpose language, designed and developed by Jeff Bezason, Alan Edelman, Viral B. Shah and Stefan Karpinski in MIT. For years, the requirements of a language of having, on one hand, a clear, simple syntax, easy readability, and good abstraction capabilities, while in the other hand being designed for technical, high-performance and resource-intensive computations, have been thought as mutually exclusive. This led applied scientists to face the task of not only learning two different languages –one high-level, the other low-level-, but also learning how to communicate between them, which is far from trivial in a lot of cases. This is called the two language problem, and it costs programmers and scientists valuable time and effort which may be better to invest in solving the underlying true problems, which required of computations to be tackled in the first place. This is where Julia makes its appeareance, intending to bridge the gap present in the two language problem, designed from its roots for being fast and easy to understand, even for people who are not programmers or computer scientists. Julia is dynamically typed and is great for interactive use. It also uses multiple dispatch as a core design concept, which adds to the composability of the language. In conventional, single-dispatched, object-oriented programming languages, when invoking a method, one of the arguments is treated specially and it determines which of all the methods with that same name is going to be appled. Multiple dispatch is a generalization of this for all the arguments of the function called, so the method applied is going to be the one that matches exactly the the number of type of the function call.

As you can see, writing Julia code is pretty straight-forward. First of all, we made some variable assignaments, variables n1, n2 and m were asigned with values 0, 1 and 10. Then, we defined a function for the fibonacci calculation. Function blocks start with the function statement, followed by the name of the function and the arguments within brackets. This arguments will be the two first numbers of the sequence and the total length of the sequence. Inside the function definition, first we initialize an array of integers of one dimention and length m. This way of initializing an array is not strictly necessary, but is definitely a good practice for optimizing code performance in Julia. Don't worry too much about that right now, though. We then proceed to assign the two first elements of the sequence and calculate the rest with a for loop. The syntax 3:m just means all the numbers from 3 to m, with a step of 1. We could have set 3:2:m if we wanted a step of 2 between each iteration. Finally, an end statement is necessary at the end of the for loop, as well as for ending the function definition. You may have noticed que exclamation mark (or 'bang', as it is called in the Julia community) next to the scatter function. What the scatter!() call then does, is to modify the global state of the plot in-place. If not done this way, both plots wouldn't be sketched together.

Introduction to Bayes

5.5 μs

Uncertainty is our brains' common currency. It naturally knows, for example, how plausible an event is. We know that some events, as a big volcano eruption are rare, and some others like rain are more common. This plausibility and our understanding of the world in general depends heavily on the data we measure, in other words, our past observations, and the model we have about the world. For example, we know that in the desert is less likely to rain that in a Caribbean town. We infer that because we have an internal model for such events. As we grew up, those models changed with time, we have updated them as we collected new data, had new experiences. It that sense, we are all the time interacting with new stimuli, thinking how to react and, based on past experience, what we need to do next in order to have the outcome we want.

It would be nice and useful to think about problems in that way, firstly because we can relate very much with this approach of solving problems, and also because it allows us to make models, using previous information or intuition (an arguable word for experience) and working with uncertainty in such a natural way, arising as an intrinsic property of the data and how we measure it.

A Bayesian way of thinking aligns very good with this train of thought. These groups of techniques are not new, in fact they even were the first conceptions of what we call now probability and statistics, formulated mathematically speaking by Thomas Bayes and published posthumously in 1763.

But before explicitly digging into a Bayesian framework and explaining how to express those ideas in a more mathematical way, we are going to introduce some concepts first that will help us to a better and deep understanding.

13.4 μs

Distributions and sampling

3 μs

Distributions and histograms

We have talked about events, but how are they related to probability? A probability distribution is a function that tells us how likely is an event to occur and it can take values between 0 and 1. Events with a probability near to 0 are less likely to occur, on the contrary, events near to 1 are more likely to happen. Probability distributions can have very different and interesting properties and shapes, they can express the probability of continuous events, such as height or amount of rainfall, but also they can map discrete events, such as heads in N flips of a coin, to its probability.

10.7 μs

To illustrate some of these concepts, we are going to use monthly rainfall data from the city of Buenos Aires, Argentina, since 1991. The histogram of the data is shown below. An histogram is a plot that tells us the relative frequency of events, it's just a representation for the action of counting event.

But why am I inferring how likely is an event to happen in the future with data from the past?

I'm making some assumptions that are often implied working with histograms and measured data: the first assumption is that the data is representative for the variable in consideration, meaning that the data of rainfall was measured well, that it isn't measured just during winter for example, when we know rainfall is most common. The other big assumption is that things in the future will not change much from things in the past, so if we do the measure again for some time in the near future, the shape of the histogram is going to be more or less the same.

4.5 μs

Sampling

Let's introduce now an important concept: sampling.

To clarify the concept, we will run a mental experiment: suppose we want to guess how will look like the histogram of the data for the rainfall in Buenos Aires if we collect measurements for the next 5 years.

Do really we need to wait to have a 'sample' of the experiment?

The answer is no. We already know that the shape of the histogram will be similar to one we have with the values measured before. All we need to do is to 'create' a series of plausible values. There are a couple of simple methods to do that. For example, we could draw a random coordinate, like in the plot shown below, with x values between 0 and 440 and y values between 0 and 0.007, if the point lays in the blue region (any bar from the histogram) we take the point as a plausible sample, but if the point falls outside any blue bar, we discard the point. In the plot 2 points are draw, a green point and red point, taking the first as a plausible point and discarding the second one.

43.5 ms

We encourage the reader to apply this method for multiple points and plot the histogram of the plausible points. It does look similar to the one we have before, right?.

But instead of the method we have described, we are going to use some built in methods.

Now that we have the concept of sampling, we could point out why this will help us. At the beginning we said that in a Bayesian framework, we have a model of the problem we want to address and maybe some data we want to use. So, we want somehow to use the data to update our model, also maybe to fit a parameter we don't know its value or simply to guess what are the more plausible values for the parameters of the model we propose. In order to answer those very important questions we need sampling, infering how plausible are the parameters' values with the data we have, again by sampling.

19.9 μs
Example: Flipping a coin
11.7 μs
19.7 ms

We are going now to explain a well known example: flipping a coin, but from a Bayesian perspective ;).

So the problem goes like this:

Suppose we flip a coin N times, and we ask our self some questions like :

  • Is having heads as likely as having tails?

  • Is our coin biased, preferring one output over the other?

To answer these questions we are going to build a simple model.

First at all: Do we have prior information about the problem? Well, yes, we do. We know that the value of p (since is the probability of having heads) lays between 0 and 1.

Do we know anything more?

Let's skip that question for the moment and suppose we don't know anything more about p. Not knowing anything is also some kind of information for my model.

How?

Because we can assign equal probability for each value of p between 0 and 1, and 0 probability for the remaing values. So, translating that into a probability distribution, it means that we are going to use a Uniform prior distribution for p and this uniform distribution between 0 and 1.

Why 'prior'?

We will explain that in just a moment, but you can gess why.

39.3 μs

The histogram of p build with sampled values from out prior uniform distribution is shown below:

8.2 μs
23.6 ms

We see that the plot is almost a straight line, the almost comes from the fact that we are sampling an uniform distribution.

4.6 μs

Continuing with the problem, how do we model the outcomes of flipping a coin?

Well, if we search for some similar type of experiment we find that all processes in which we have 2 possible outcomes, heads or tails in this case, and a probability of success p (probability of heads) are called Bernoulli trials. Therefore we are going to model the outcome with a bernoulli distribution, which has p as a parameter.

But how do we update out bernoulli model with the outcomes we had flipping the coin?

Bayes' theorem comes in to help us now.

10.3 μs

Bayes theorem

3.1 μs

Now we are going to explain a bit more about a theorem used in all Bayesian frameworks, that is the Bayes' theorem.

The theorem goes like this:

P(A|B)=P(B|A)P(A)P(B)

where P(A|B) are called conditional probabilities, the probability of the event A given that B has occurred.

How does this theorem relate to our Bayesian perspective of solving problems?

Well, actually by analysing the equation we can summarize a lot of what we have talked about updating models with data. If we consider P(A) to be our prior knowledge about the problem, and B the data we have, then P(B|A) is the plausibility of the data given the model we have proposed. On the other hand, P(A|B) is the plausibility of the model given the data, and that is what we want to know!!. The remaining term P(B) is just a normalization to preserve the properties of a probability distribution: that summing the probability of all event adds up to 1, so don't worry about it.

15.8 μs

To summarize, the left side of the equation can be interpreted as updating our beliefs by multiplying the prior distribution, that is P(A), with P(B|A), called the likelihood distribution. Now that we know how the bayes theorem works, we are going to continue with our problem.

9.7 μs

The model coinflip receives the N outcomes of our flips, a vector of lenght N with 0 or 1 values, 0 values indicating fails or an outcome of tails and 1 indicating sucesses or heads. The idea is that with each new value of outcome, the model will be updating its believes about the parameter p and this is what the for loop is doing: we are saying that each outcome comes from a Bernoulli distribution with a parameter p, a success probability, shared for all the outcomes.

What if we wanted to include more previous knowledge about the success rate p?

Let's say we know that the value of p is near 0.5 but we are not so sure about the exact value, and we want the model to find the plausibility for the values of p. Then including this knowledge, our prior distribution for p will have higher probability for values near 0.5, and low probability for values near 0 or 1. Seaching again in our repertoire of distributions, one that fulfill our wishes is a Beta distribution with parameters α=2 and β=2. It is ploted below.

To illustrate the affirmation made before, we can compare for example the posterior distributions obtained only with the first 4 outcomes for both models, the one with a uniform prior and the other with the beta prior. The plots are shown below. We see that some values near 0 and 1 have still high probability for the model with a uniform prior for p, while in the model with a beta prior the values near 0.5 have higher probability. That's because if we tell the model from the beginning that p near 0 and 1 have less probability, it catchs up faster that probabilities near 0.5 are higher.

4.9 μs
647 μs

So in this case, incorporating our beliefs in the prior distribution we saw the model reached faster the more plausible values for p, needing less outcomes to reach a very similar posterior distribution. When we used an uniform prior, we were conservative, meaning that we said we didn't know anything about p so we assign equal probability for all values. Sometimes these kind of distribution (uniform distributions), called a non-informative prior, can be maybe too conservative, being in some cases not helpful at all. They even can slow the convergence of the model to the more plausible values for our posterior, as shown.

5.5 μs
